<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
    @make_header OpenPCells Documentation
    <body>
        @make_topbar Technology Files
        <details open>
            <summary>Introduction</summary>
            <p>
            This guide shows the process of adding new technology files.
            Technology files are required to generate layouts for specific and real technology nodes.
            Internally, openPCells has a generic model of a layer stack, which is then translated to the actual layer stack.
            Additionally, openPCells must know how to create via arrays, because in most technology nodes there are only very limited ways of creating via cuts.
            Also a few technology properties should need to be known to support the internal parametric cells of the OpenPCells project.
            All required definitions and files will be described and explained subsequently.
            </p>
            <p>
            In general the (non-physical) <code class="shellinline">opc</code> technology supplied by the openPCells project can be used as a starting point and reference.
            It is used internally to test functionality and cells.
            </p>
        </details>

        <details open>
            <summary>Adding Technologies</summary>
            <p>
            A technology node definition is a collection of files in one directory.
            These files get loaded by opc when requested as technology, the directory has to be within one of the paths in the technology search path (see the <code class="shellinline">--techpath</code> command line option).
            OpenPCells expects a technology to provide at least four files: 
            </p>
            <ul class="description-list">
                <li>
                    config.lua
                    <p>
                    Defines key features of a technology, such as whether the node is an SOI node, whether it has triple wells etc.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    layermap.lua
                    <p>
                    Defines mapping of generic layers to specific layers.
                    Several export types can be supported (e.g. gds, SKILL, etc.)
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    vias.lua
                    <p>
                    Defines possible arrayzations of via cuts depending on the cut size, required enclosures and x- and y-spacings.
                    Multiple entries can be given for via cuts, to support more complex design rules.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    constraints.lua
                    <p>
                    Defines minimum/maximum values for critical geometric values, such as &quot;Minimum M1 Width&quot;.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>

            <p>
            All these files must return exactly one lua table, so a basic (empty) technology file has the following content:
            </p>
            <pre class="opc"><code>return {} </code></pre>
            <p>
            Of course, this does not really make sense, so the following sections explore what (and when) to put into these files.
            </p>
            <p>
            The four files need to be present and some definitions in them are mandatory.
            Each of them will be explained in more detail subsequently.
            </p>
        </details>

        <details open>
            <summary>Config</summary>
            <p>
            The config file requires a few keys set.
            The technology loading routine looks for certain fields, but there is no definite list of required features.
            At the moment of this writing the config file supports the following properties:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li>
                    <code class="luainline">grid</code>
                    <p>Sets the manufacturing grid. Expects an integer. Mandatory.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="luainline">metals</code>
                    <p>Sets the number of metals. Expects an integer. Mandatory.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="luainline">multiple_patterning</code>
                    <p>Defines multiple-patterning for some metals. Here a table is expected, with a table entry for every multiple-patterning metal like this: <code class="luainline">{ metal = 1, number = 2 }</code> (for two masks for metal 1). This entry is optional.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="luainline">is_soi</code>
                    <p>Defines whether this node is a silicon-on-insulator process. Expects a boolean. Mandatory.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="luainline">allow_poly_routing</code>
                    <p>Defines whether the gate material (polysilicon) can be used for routing, allowing arbitrary shapes on poly. Expects a boolean. Mandatory.</p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <code class="luainline">has_gatecut</code>
                    <p>Defines whether this technology has support for gate cutting layers. Expects a boolean. Mandatory.</p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
            More options are also likely to come.
            </p>
            <p>
            An example of a possible config file (taken from the <code class="shellinline">opc</code> technology files) is given below:
            </p>
            <pre class="opc"><code>return {
    grid = 1,
    metals = 10,
    allow_poly_routing = false,
    is_soi = false,
    has_gatecut = false,
}</code></pre>
        </details>

        <details open>
            <summary>Layermap</summary>
            <p>
            The layers in openPCells are defined in general layers (such as "gate" or "M1" or "lastmetal"), which have to be translated into a specific technology for cell generation.
            In order to make it easy to start with techfiles they only need to contain what is required by the generated cell.
            That means for example that for an inductor with only one metal layer only the mapping for that metal is required.
            If a cell is generated where some layers are missing in the techfile, you will see the following message (with the requested layer listed, in this case <code class="shellinline">metal(2)</code>):
            </p>
            <pre class="shell"><code>generics: got NULL layer: generics.metal(2)
if this layer is not needed, set it to {} </code></pre>
            <p>
            This message shows you which layer has to be added to the techfile in order to make the cell run successfully.
            This section will explain how to add these layers and which information is required.
            </p>
            <p>
            The layermap shall define entries for specific layers, which are pre-defined within openPCells.
            The layers use symbolic names such as <code class="luainline">generics.well("n")</code>, which have no physical correspondence in the specific technology node.
            Hence the layermap provides a mapping from these symbolic layers to specific representation.
            The mapping can include a variety of things, the required data within the definition depend on the used export.
            For instance, the gds export needs a layer number and a purpose pair (so-called layer-purpose-pair, lpp).
            The SKILL export also uses these properties, but as human-readable strings, not numbers.
            Other exports are easy to add, the layermap does not restrict the internal representation.
            </p>
            <p>
            Every entry of the layermap is a table which contains a sub-table (with the key <code class="luainline">layer</code>) which defines one entry for every supported export.
            An example given below shows a layer map that defines (only) the first metal layer, <code class="luainline">M1</code>:
            </p>
            <pre class="opc"><code>return { -- top-level table
    -- example for metal 1
    M1 = {
        name = "metal1",
        layer = {
            gds = { layer = 8, purpose = 0 },
            SKILL = { layer = "metal1", purpose = "drawing" },
            svg = { style = "metal1", order = 4, color = "0000ff" },
        }
    },
}</code></pre>
            <p>
            The required layers are currently not strictly defined.
            For one, this depends on the actual technology node, as different technology nodes might need different layers and have more a fewer metal layers.
            Additionally, OpenPCells does not really define required layers.
            This happens implicitly by the needs of the used pcells.
            Therefore, for adding new technologies one can simply use the simplest layermap until opc reports missing layers.
            A list of required layers for a standard triple-well p-bulk CMOS process node is given by the following list:
            </p>
            <ul class="description-list">
                <li>
                    active
                    <p>
                    The layer for active diffusions.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    gate
                    <p>
                    The layer for gates, usually polysilicon.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    contactactive, contactsourcedrain contactgate, contactpoly
                    <p>
                    The layer for contacts from the specified regions (e.g. &quot;active&quot;) to the first interconnect layer.
                    Some technology nodes use the same contact for all these regions, others might not, hence they are separated.
                    If these don't have to be distinguished, they can simply be all mapped to the same content.
                    &quot;sourcedrain&qout; contacts are the contacts from the source drain regions, &quot;gate&quot; contacts the gates.
                    &quot;active&qout; and &qout;poly&quot; physically contact the same regions, but there might be extra contacts to contact raw polysilicon (for instance for a resistor) instead of polysilicon-for-gates.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    pimplant
                    <p>
                    The layer for p-implants for forming p-diffusions.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    nimplant
                    <p>
                    The layer for p-implants for forming n-diffusions.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    nwell
                    <p>
                    The layer for n-wells.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    deepnwell
                    <p>
                    The layer for deep n-wells, for forming isolated p-wells in a triple-well process.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    oxide&lt;N&gt;
                    <p>
                    The layer for oxide thickness modification.
                    Typically, oxide1 is an empty layer and thicker oxides are then achieved with oxide2, but this can be defined differently.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    metal&lt;N&gt;
                    <p>
                    The &lt;N&gt;th metal, where &lt;N&gt; starts at 1.
                    The first metal does not need to be an actual metal, it should be the lowest interconnect layer above the active/gate regions (not contacts).
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    viacutM&lt;N&gt;M&lt;N + 1&gt;
                    <p>
                    The via cut layer from metal &lt;N&gt; to &lt;N + 1&gt;.
                    Theoretically direct vias from, say, M1 to M3 are possible, but internally one-level vias (e.g. viacutM1M2) are assumed.
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
            The layer mappings also allow a field <code class="opcinline">name</code>. This is optional, but helps when debugging cells.
            </p>
            <p>
            The layermap keys (e.g. &quot;M1&quot;) require knowledge of the internal naming scheme of layers.
            This is now considered the legacy way of specifying layer names.
            Recent OpenPCells releases support the use of the layer names as they are used in layout files:
            </p>
            <pre class="opc"><code>return {
    [generics.active()] = ...,
    [generics.gate()] = ...,
    [generics.implant("p")] = ...,
    [generics.metal(1)] = ...,
    [generics.viacut(1, 2)] = ...,
}</code></pre>
            <p>
            The use of the square brackets around the key names is required by lua, as otherwise the key is read as a string in the form of a standard lua identifier.
            Without the brackets the lua compiler will raise syntax errors.
            </p>
        </details>

        <details open>
            <summary>Vias</summary>
                <p>
                The via rules file defines the via/contact geometries.
                In general, via regions (specified as rectangles within cells) are turned into arrays of individual cuts, defined by the via technology file.
                Therefore, the cut sizing must be given (<code class="opcinline">width</code> and <code class="opcinline">height</code>) as well as minimum space in x- and y-direction as well as outer enclosure (often different then inter-cut spacing).
                </p>
                <p>
                Multiple entries are possible to accomodate the different ways of drawing vias.
                Furthermore, via entries can be restricted to certain maximum widths and/or heights of the via regions, with the keys <code class="opcinline">maxwidth</code> and <code class="opcinline">maxheight</code>.
                The following example is adapted from the <code class="shellinline">opc</code> technology files:
                </p>
                <pre class="opc"><code>viaM1M2 = {
    entries = {
        {
            width = 100, height = 100,
            xspace = 200, yspace = 200,
            xenclosure = 50, yenclosure = 50
        },
        {
            width = 100, height = 100,
            xspace = 200, yspace = 200,
            xenclosure = 100, yenclosure = 20
        },
    },
}, </code></pre>
                <p>
                In their simplest form, vias have the same enclosures for both layers.
                However, this is not true for many technology nodes.
                For competitive DRC-clean vias more complex definitions are sometimes required.
                In this case, the enclosures can be given separately for both layers:
                </p>
                <pre class="opc"><code>viaM1M2 = {
    entries = {
        {
            width = 100, height = 100,
            xspace = 200, yspace = 200,
            xenclosure1 = 50, yenclosure1 = 50
            xenclosure2 = 80, yenclosure2 = 80
        },
    },
}, </code></pre>
                <p>
                These viacut values are used for the via*2 and contact*2 functions, which are used internally in several cells, especially <code class="luainline">basic/mosfet</code>.
                </p>
        </details>

        <details open>
            <summary>Constraints</summary>
                <p>
                The constraints file defines critical geometric values as base values for parametric cells.
                This includes values as the minimum gate length, minimum metal spacing and more.
                The required values depend on the used cells:
                As with other properties in the technology files, only those which are required by the used cells need to be defined.
                However, below an example of a constraint file will be given that satisfies the needs of the standard opc cells.
                </p>
                <pre class="opc"><code>return {
    ["Default Label Size"]                          = 200,
    -- active diffusion constraints
    ["Minimum Active Width"]                        = 200,
    ["Minimum Active Space"]                        = 200,
    -- gate constraints
    ["Minimum Gate Extension"]                      = 100,
    ["Minimum Gate Length"]                         = 200,
    ["Minimum Gate Width"]                          = 500,
    ["Minimum Gate XSpace"]                         = 300,
    ["Minimum Gate YSpace"]                         = 300,
    -- minimum size for source/drain contacts
    ["Minimum Source/Drain Contact Region Size"]    = 280,
    -- minimum size for active contacts
    ["Minimum Active Contact Region Size"]          = 280,
    -- minimum size for gate contacts
    ["Minimum Gate Contact Region Size"]            = 280,
    -- minimum FEOL layer extensions
    ["Minimum Well Extension"]                      = 100,
    ["Minimum Implant Extension"]                   = 100,
    ["Minimum Oxide Extension"]                     = 80,
    ["Minimum Silicideblocker Extension"]           = 200,
    -- metal definitions
    ["Minimum M1 Width"]                            = 200,
    ["Minimum M1 Space"]                            = 200,
    -- more metals...
    ["Minimum M1M2 Viawidth"]                       = 260,
    -- more vias...
}</code></pre>
                <p>
                Most constraints should be self-explanatory.
                The Viawidth entries are different from the metal width entries in that OpenPCells expects to be able to find a legal via arrayzation in a square region with that size.
                Some default parameters of the opc pcells use these values, so make sure that the given viawidths match at least one entry in the via arrayzation file (vias.lua), or the cell generation will fail.
                This is important as debugging why a generation fails is hard without a layout to look at.
                If metal spacings or widths are too small, the layout can still be looked at, it will just not be DRC clean.
                <p>
        </details>

        <details open>
            <summary>Summary</summary>
            <p>
            This already concludes the information on writing techfiles.
            There are some subleties here and there, but this document should be enough to get a basic technology mapping going.
            In general, the more advanced the used cells are, the more complex these files will get.
            This means on the other hand that only a few lines in each of these files are already enough to start using some of the cells and learning the opc workflow.
            </p>
        </details>

        @include footer.html
    </body>
</html>

<!--
            Furthermore, vias and contacts have to be put into arrays, which requires knowledge about the technology.
            The technology-defining files (the \enquote{techfiles}) describe the required rules and layer mappings.
-->
